The default implementation lives in StackIterable and is:
    @Override
    default MutableStack<T> toStack()
    {
        return Stacks.mutable.withAllReversed(this);
    }
Which is implemented in MutableStackFactoryImpl
    @Override
    public <T> MutableStack<T> withAllReversed(Iterable<? extends T> items)
    {
        return ArrayStack.newStackFromTopToBottom(items);
    }
So yes it's safe. I don't remember why we wrote this. Sometimes we've created patterns like this as an optimization, but I rarely want to do that. It would have to be for one of the most common iteration patterns and one of the most common collections to make it worth even performance testing.
